						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">thefox wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">While it's a good idea to use <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">copydata</tt> to restore the standard C behavior, alternatively you can simply make sure to initialize the global variables in your own code before using them.</div><br />It's a standard C language feature, and the C compiler depends on it. Omitting it silently breaks your code, as we've seen. It has no way of knowing that you've removed that essential step in the CRT init, so there's no way it can produce an error to prevent you from using the feature.</div><br />There's one way to get warnings -- set the DATA segment type to &quot;bss&quot;, linker should then give a warning when initialized data is placed in the segment.<br /><br />Anyway, I moreso meant to present manual initialization as a quick hack rather than a real alternative for fixing the initialization code. I could've been more clear about that.</div>

					
